            "answer_text": "The FLT proof is a clear cut proof, checked over and again by the experts and part of the community, so there is no \u201cmight\u201d or \u201ccould\u201d involved. Wiles\u2019 work did actually close the last gap; he was building on other people\u2019s previous work, that has been equally checked and verified: Gerhard Frey constructed a mathematical object, called an Elliptic curve, out of an assumed \u201cFermat Triple\u201d (a,b,c). Kenneth Ribet, following suggestions by the great Jean-Pierre Serre, was able to show that the Frey curve, if it really existed (so if FLT was false) was a non-modular curve. The \u201cgap\u201d mentioned above was the proof of the Shimura-Taniyama-Weil conjecture, which asserts that every elliptic curve is modular. Wiles was able to prove (jointly with his graduate student Richard Taylor) a special case (so-called semi-stable curves) that covers the Frey-curve. I am explaining this is this detail, because you have to understand, that in today\u2019s mathematics deep results are practically never an achievement of a single mathematician working in isolation. There is a wealth of partial results, of reductions to special cases, or a link to an equivalent problem. Working mathematicians will have to learn and understand all this. I want to give you another example: the proof of the Poincare conjecture by Grigori Perelman (who solved one of the Clay Millennium Problems with his result). Originally formulated as a conjecture on the 3-dimensional sphere in 4-space (the lower dimensions being well-known already at that time), it was generalized to all higher dimensions pretty quickly. Stephen Smale established Poincare for dimensions greater than or equal to 5 in 1962 with a then novel tool called Morse Theory (which is until today a valuable tool for topologists). He received the Fields Medal for his achievement in 1966. In 1982 Michael Freedman proved the case n=4 with a completely different set of techniques. So the original case n=3 was open. Bill Thurston generalized again \u2014 this time by introducing geometrical structures on 3-dimensional manifolds in general, and conjecturing, that each 3-manifold would carry such a geometric structure (very roughly; apologies to topologists \u2026). Poincare would follow as a consequence of a proof of Thurston\u2019s conjecture. Again the \u201ccomplex case\u201d, for manifolds with rich topology, was established quickly. To tackle the remaining cases, Richard Hamilton introduced a new analytic tool, the so-called Ricci-Flow, which \u201cpulls\u201d a curved space at each point into the direction and with the speed of the local curvature. The application to Thurston and Poincare conjectures failed eventually, because nobody was able to handle the singularities, that could appear in Hamilton\u2019s Ricci flow. Enter Perelman: he introduced new analytic tools, and was able to show that the Ricci flow could be regularized, and that the singularities could be handled in a satisfactory manner. So you see: there is another famous case, where the mathematician who delivers the final proof, did not go the whole way, but built on many, partially brilliant previous results and ideas. ",
