            "answer_text": "He proved Fermat's Last theorem. Mathematicians are very particular. \u201cMight imply it to be true\u201d is not good enough for a mathematician. In the simplest form possible how Wiles proved it: He assumed that there was a counterexample. And he showed that any counterexample will hold contradictory properties. What I mean by contradictory properties is that it provably has two properties that don't go together. For example if I were to prove that a number were simultaneously even and odd, that would be problematic. The exact details of the proof are extensive and complicated, and I am unfortunately not equipped to understand most of it. But this is a simpler version of what my number theory professor explained to me. ",
